liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: The wait is over! The Rolling Stones have announced their first album in 18 years — since 2005's A Bigger Bang. Titled Hackney Diamonds, the band will share details of the release at an event in East London's Hackney district on Wednesday, where they'll be interviewed live by The Tonight Show host Jimmy Fallon. "Hackney may be at the heart of Hackney Diamonds, but this is a truly global moment we want to share with fans around the world via YouTube," the Rolling Stones shared in a statement. The album is also the Stones' first since the death of drummer Charlie Watts in 2021.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: The Rolling Stones to release first studio album in 18 years

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: A group of federal politicians will head to the United States this month to lobby for the release of Julian Assange. The US is seeking to extradite the WikiLeaks founder from London, on charges of espionage. Prime Minister Anthony Albanese has previously expressed frustration that a diplomatic solution for Julian Assange's case has not been reached. The delegation that will head to the US includes Nationals MP Barnaby Joyce, Labor MP Tony Zappia and Independent MP Monique Ryan. It comes ahead of Albanese's trip to Washington in October.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Federal politicians to head to the US to lobby for Julian Assange's release

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Economists are expecting the Reserve Bank to keep interest rates at 4.1 per cent today, as 11-year high borrowing costs slow demand. The Reserve Bank has passed through four percentage points worth of rate hikes since May last year in a bid to curb sky-high inflation. That's starting to have an effect, with monthly inflation figures released last week showing another bigger-than-forecast decline to 4.9 per cent, down from 5.4 per cent in June. Most economists say this means it's likely the RBA will keep interest rates at 4.1 per cent for a third straight month. It marks the final meeting for outgoing governor Philip Lowe, who hands over to Michele Bullock later this month.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Philip Lowe to deliberate on final interest rate decision as RBA governor
